FILED SENATE
Apr 30, 2026
GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
S.B. 966
SESSION 2025
PRINCIPAL CLERK
S D
SENATE BILL DRS35424-NBf-182
Short Title: The SAVE Act. (Public)
Sponsors: Senators Burgin and Hise (Primary Sponsors).
Referred to:
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO DEFINE THE PRACTICE OF NURSING FOR ADVANCED PRACTICE
3 REGISTERED NURSES: NURSE PRACTITIONERS (NP), CERTIFIED NURSE
4 MIDWIVES (CNM), CERTIFIED REGISTERED NURSE ANESTHETISTS (CRNA),
5 AND CLINICAL NURSE SPECIALISTS (CNS).
6 Whereas, North Carolina is expected to be the seventh largest state in the nation by
7 2035 and demand for health care will continue to increase; and
8 Whereas, North Carolina has provided over 628,000 North Carolinians access to
9 insurance through Medicaid expansion but lacks the health care providers to ensure their access
10 to care; and
11 Whereas, APRNs are registered nurses with master's or doctorate degrees and
12 advanced education and training; and
13 Whereas, North Carolina has over 20,000 advanced practice registered nurses
14 (APRNs) who have been educated and licensed to practice to their full scope; and
15 Whereas, more than three decades of research demonstrates that APRNs improve
16 access to safe, high-quality, cost-effective, patient-centered health care; and
17 Whereas, the Institute of Medicine (IOM) has called for states to allow APRNs to
18 practice to the full extent of their licensure and education since the 2010 release of the IOM
19 Report on the Future of Nursing; and
20 Whereas, health care costs in North Carolina are among the highest in the nation; and
21 Whereas, a recent report by a Ph.D. health care economist at Duke University
22 estimates savings of at least $700 million annually for North Carolina patients, employers, and
23 taxpayers by removing unnecessary and antiquated government regulations; and
24 Whereas, 36 other states have rolled back these costly and burdensome government
25 regulations on advanced practice registered nurses over the past 31 years with no evidence of
26 negative effects on patient safety, and indeed positive impact on patient care, according to
27 numerous studies; and
28 Whereas, no state has enacted these reforms and later reversed course to reinstate
29 these government regulations; and
30 Whereas, the APRN role has existed for over a half century but remains undefined in
31 North Carolina statute; and
32 Whereas, North Carolina's courts and executive branch have called on the legislature,
33 the body of the people, to remove the ambiguity surrounding APRN practice by clearly defining
34 it in statute; Now, therefore,
35 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
36 SECTION 1. G.S. 90-171.20 reads as rewritten:
*DRS35424-NBf-182*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 "§ 90-171.20. Definitions.
2 As used in this Article, unless the context requires otherwise:
3 (1) Advanced assessment. – The taking by an advanced practice registered nurse
4 of the history, physical, and psychological assessment of a patient's signs,
5 symptoms, pathophysiologic status, and psychosocial variations in the
6 determination of differential diagnoses and treatment.
7 (1a) Advanced practice registered nurse or APRN. – An individual licensed by the
8 Board as an advanced practice registered nurse within one of the following
9 four roles:
10 a. Certified nurse practitioner or CNP.
11 b. Certified nurse midwife or CNM.
12 c. Clinical nurse specialist or CNS.
13 d. Certified registered nurse anesthetist or CRNA.
14 (1b) "Board" means the Board. – The North Carolina Board of Nursing.
15 (2) "Health care provider" means any Health care provider. – Any licensed health
16 care professional and any agent or employee of any health care institution,
17 health care insurer, health care professional school, or a member of any allied
18 health profession. For purposes of this Article, a person enrolled in a program
19 that prepares the person to be a licensed health care professional or an allied
20 health professional shall be deemed a health care provider.
21 (3) "License" means a License. – A permit issued by the Board to practice nursing
22 as an advanced practice registered nurse, as a registered nurse nurse, or as a
23 licensed practical nurse, including a renewal or reinstatement thereof.
24 (3a) "Licensee" means any Licensee. – Any person issued a license by the Board,
25 whether the license is active or inactive, including an inactive license by
26 means of surrender.
27 (4) "Nursing" is a Nursing. – A dynamic discipline which includes the assessing,
28 caring, counseling, teaching, referring and implementing of prescribed
29 treatment in the maintenance of health, prevention and management of illness,
30 injury, disability or the achievement of a dignified death. It is ministering to;
31 assisting; and sustained, vigilant, and continuous care of those acutely or
32 chronically ill; supervising patients during convalescence and rehabilitation;
33 the supportive and restorative care given to maintain the optimum health level
34 of individuals, groups, and communities; the supervision, teaching, and
35 evaluation of those who perform or are preparing to perform these functions;
36 and the administration of nursing programs and nursing services. For purposes
37 of this Article, the administration of required lethal substances or any
38 assistance whatsoever rendered with an execution under Article 19 of Chapter
39 15 of the General Statutes does not constitute nursing.
40 (5) "Nursing program" means any Nursing program. – Any educational program
41 in North Carolina offering to prepare persons to meet the educational
42 requirements for licensure under this Article.Article as a registered nurse or a
43 licensed practical nurse.
44 (6) "Person" means an Person. – An individual, corporation, partnership,
45 association, unit of government, or other legal entity.
46 (6a) Population focus. – With respect to APRN practice, includes one of the
47 following areas of focus:
48 a. The family or the individual across the life span.
49 b. Adult/gerontology.
50 c. Neonatal.
51 d. Pediatrics.
Page 2 DRS35424-NBf-182

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 e. Women's health or gender-related issues.
2 f. Psychiatric mental health.
3 (6b) Practice of nursing as a certified nurse midwife or CNM. – In addition to the
4 RN scope of practice and APRN role and population foci, also consists of the
5 following four components:
6 a. The management, diagnosis, and treatment of primary sexual and
7 reproductive health care, including primary, preconception,
8 gynecologic/reproductive/sexual health, antepartum, intrapartum,
9 neonatal, and post-pregnancy care.
10 b. Ordering, performing, supervising, and interpreting diagnostic studies.
11 c. Prescribing pharmacologic and nonpharmacologic therapies.
12 d. Consulting with or referring to other health care providers as
13 warranted by the needs of the patient.
14 (6c) Practice of nursing as a certified nurse practitioner or CNP. – In addition to
15 the RN scope of practice and APRN role and population foci, also consists of
16 the following six components:
17 a. Health promotion, disease prevention, health education, and
18 counseling.
19 b. Providing health assessment and screening activities.
20 c. Diagnosing, treating, and facilitating patients' management of their
21 acute and chronic illnesses and diseases.
22 d. Ordering, performing, supervising, and interpreting diagnostic studies.
23 e. Prescribing pharmacologic and nonpharmacologic therapies.
24 f. Consulting with or referring to other health care providers as
25 warranted by the needs of the patient.
26 (6d) Practice of nursing as a certified registered nurse anesthetist or CRNA. – In
27 addition to the RN scope of practice and within the APRN role and population
28 foci, also consists of the following:
29 a. Selecting, ordering, procuring, prescribing, and administering drugs
30 and therapeutic devices to facilitate diagnostic, therapeutic, and
31 surgical procedures.
32 b. Ordering, prescribing, performing, supervising, and interpreting
33 diagnostic studies, procedures, and interventions.
34 c. Consulting with or referring to other health care providers as
35 warranted by the needs of the patient.
36 (6e) Practice of nursing as a clinical nurse specialist or CNS. – In addition to the
37 RN scope of practice and APRN role and population foci, also consists of the
38 following eight components:
39 a. The diagnosis and treatment of health and illness states.
40 b. Disease management.
41 c. Prescribing pharmacologic and nonpharmacologic therapies.
42 d. Ordering, performing, supervising, and interpreting diagnostic studies.
43 e. Prevention of illness and risk behaviors.
44 f. Nursing care for individuals, families, and communities.
45 g. Integrating care across the continuum to improve patient outcomes.
46 h. Consulting with or referring to other health care providers as
47 warranted by the needs of the patient.
48 (6f) Practice of nursing as an advanced practice registered nurse or APRN. – In
49 addition to the RN scope of practice and within the APRN role and population
50 foci, also consists of the following six components:
51 a. Conducting an advanced assessment.
DRS35424-NBf-182 Page 3

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 b. Delegating and assigning therapeutic measures to assistive personnel.
2 c. Performing other acts that require education and training consistent
3 with professional standards and commensurate with the APRN's
4 education, certification, demonstrated competencies, and experience.
5 d. Complying with the requirements of this Article and rendering quality
6 advanced nursing care.
7 e. Recognizing limits of knowledge and experience.
8 f. Planning for the management of situations beyond the APRN's
9 expertise.
10 (7) The "practice of nursing by a registered nurse" consists Practice of nursing by
11 a registered nurse. – Consists of the following 10 components:
12 a. Assessing the patient's physical and mental health, including the
13 patient's reaction to illnesses and treatment regimens.
14 b. Recording and reporting the results of the nursing assessment.
15 c. Planning, initiating, delivering, and evaluating appropriate nursing
16 acts.
17 d. Teaching, assigning, delegating to or supervising other personnel in
18 implementing the treatment regimen.
19 e. Collaborating with other health care providers in determining the
20 appropriate health care for a patient but, subject to the provisions of
21 G.S. 90-18.2, not prescribing a medical treatment regimen or making
22 a medical diagnosis, except under supervision of a licensed
23 physician.patient.
24 f. Implementing the treatment and pharmaceutical regimen prescribed or
25 ordered by any person authorized by State law to prescribe or order
26 the regimen.
27 g. Providing teaching and counseling about the patient's health.
28 h. Reporting and recording the plan for care, nursing care given, and the
29 patient's response to that care.
30 i. Supervising, teaching, and evaluating those who perform or are
31 preparing to perform nursing functions and administering nursing
32 programs and nursing services.
33 j. Providing for the maintenance of safe and effective nursing care,
34 whether rendered directly or indirectly.
35 (8) The "practice of nursing by a licensed practical nurse" consists of the
36 following seven components:
37 a. Participating in the assessment of the patient's physical and mental
38 health, including the patient's reaction to illnesses and treatment
39 regimens.
40 b. Recording and reporting the results of the nursing assessment.
41 c. Participating in implementing the health care plan developed by the
42 registered nurse and/or prescribed by any person authorized by State
43 law to prescribe such a plan, by performing tasks assigned or delegated
44 by and performed under the supervision or under orders or directions
45 of a registered nurse, physician licensed to practice medicine, dentist,
46 or other person authorized by State law to provide the supervision.
47 c1. Assigning or delegating nursing interventions to other qualified
48 personnel under the supervision of the registered nurse.
49 d. Participating in the teaching and counseling of patients as assigned by
50 a registered nurse, physician, or other qualified professional licensed
51 to practice in North Carolina.
